<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-168-428  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 168 428.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  April 3 1989 v35 n1752 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI seeks to keep FTS-2000 open; asks for no mandatory use. (MCICommunications Corp., Federal Telecommunications Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>MCI Communications Corp has requested that the General ServicesAdministration abandon its mandatory-use policy for FTS-2000, andinstead continue to rely on competitive bidding for those servicesthat would be omitted from the scope of FTS-2000.andP;  MCI'sMid-Atlantic Division vice president of government systems, JerryA. Edgerton, attempting to protect the company's right to bid ongovernment telecommunications contracts, requested by mail thatMCI and GSA representatives meet to discuss this proposedrestrictive bidding approach, which Edgerton says would return thegovernment to pre-divestiture days.andP;  Edgerton stated thatprohibiting agencies from considering FTS-2000 alternatives wouldlikely translate into windfall profits for FTS-2000 vendors at theexpense of government users.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsGovernment ContractsCompetitive BiddingFederal Telecommunications SystemUnited States. General Services Administration.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>